  "texts": [
    "In the other direction, if Y ∈ ζ F [S] ∩ X ′, then there is a y ∈ S such that Y = ζ F (y) ∈ X ′, so ζ F (y) ⊑ (F b)p X and hence ζ F (y) ⊆ X.",
    "Then y ∈ X, so ζ F (y) ∈ ζ F [X] and hence Y ∈ ζ F [X].",
    "Thus, ζ F [X] ⊇ ζ F [S] ∩ X ′.For the rest of part 1, we show that ζ F satisfies:• if y ⊑ x, then ζ F (y) ⊑ (F b)p ζ F (x) (⊑-forth); • if Y ⊑ (F b)p ζ F (x), then ∃y: y ⊑ x and ζ F (y) ⊑ (F b)p Y (⊑-back); • if xR i y, then ζ F (x)R (F b)p i ζ F (y) (R-forth); • if ζ F (x)R (F b)p i Y and Z ⊑ (F b)p Y, then ∃y: xR i y and ζ F (y) ≬ (F b)p Z (R-back).Since F is a rich and hence full possibility frame, the pull back property of ζ F follows from ⊑-forth and ⊑-back by Fact 3.5.",
    "For ⊑-forth, if y ⊑ x, thenζ F (y) ⊆ ζ F (x), so ζ F (y) ⊑ (F b)p ζ F (x).",
    "For ⊑-back, if Y ⊑ (F b)p ζ F (x), so Y ⊆ {x ′ ∈ S | x ′ ⊑ s x},then there is a y ′ ∈ Y such that y ′ ⊑ s x, which implies that there is a y ⊑ y ′ such that y ⊑ x."
